The Satisfies Operator

The `satisfies` operator (TypeScript 4.9+) checks that a value's type matches a given type without widening the value's inferred type.

### Basic Usage

```typescript
const palette = {
  red: [255, 0, 0],
  green: "#00ff00",
  blue: [0, 0, 255]
} satisfies Record<string, string | number[]>;

// Each property still has its specific type
palette.red.map(Math.round); // OK - red is number[]
palette.green.toUpperCase(); // OK - green is string
```

### Without Satisfies

```typescript
// Type annotation widens
const palette: Record<string, string | number[]> = {
  red: [255, 0, 0],
  green: "#00ff00",
  blue: [0, 0, 255]
};

// palette.red.map(Math.round); // Error: 'string | number[]' has no 'map'
```

### With Type Assertion (as)

```typescript
// This works but allows invalid values
const palette = {
  red: [255, 0, 0],
  green: "#00ff00",
  blue: [0, 0, 255]
} as Record<string, string | number[]>;

// No validation at all - anything is accepted
```

### Validating Complex Objects

```typescript
interface Color {
  hex: string;
  rgb: [number, number, number];
  name: string;
}

const colors = {
  primary: { hex: "#ff0000", rgb: [255, 0, 0], name: "Red" },
  secondary: { hex: "#00ff00", rgb: [0, 255, 0], name: "Green" }
} satisfies Record<string, Color>;

// Each color is validated against Color, but retains its exact type
console.log(colors.primary.hex.toUpperCase()); // OK
```

### Key Benefits

| Feature | Description |
|---------|------------|
| Type validation | Ensures value conforms to a type |
| Narrowed types | Retains the most specific inferred type |
| Error messages | Clear errors when validation fails |

> **Key Point:** `satisfies` validates without widening — the best of both worlds.

codeExample:
// API response validation
interface ApiConfig {
  baseUrl: string;
  headers: Record<string, string>;
  timeout: number;
}

const config = {
  baseUrl: "https://api.example.com",
  headers: {
    "Content-Type": "application/json",
    "Authorization": "Bearer token"
  },
  timeout: 5000
} satisfies ApiConfig;

// config.baseUrl retains string literal type
// config.headers has specific key types

// Nested validation
const routes = {
  home: "/",
  users: "/users/:id",
  settings: "/settings"
} satisfies Record<string, `/${string}`>;

// All routes must start with /
